The goal here is to understand the geometry of the data before you form any hypotheses. You're characterizing the raw materials, not testing anything.A. Marginal structure of candidate signals.The single most informative pre-exploration visual is a quantile-quantile plot of each candidate signal against Gaussian, faceted by time period. This tells you three things at once: tail heaviness (convex departure in tails → fat tails), discreteness or clumping (staircase patterns → stale quotes or liquidity artifacts), and non-stationarity (if the QQ shape changes across periods, the signal's distribution is drifting).For credit specifically, you'll almost always see heavy right tails in OAS and Z-spread — that's the default/distress asymmetry. The QQ plot tells you how heavy, which directly informs your choice of rank-based vs moment-based tests downstream. If the QQ plot screams "not Gaussian," you've already justified the Spearman IC choice over Pearson, and you've documented why before touching the hypothesis.B. Cross-sectional coverage and missingness heatmap.A bond × date heatmap where color encodes missingness pattern. Not just "% missing" — the structure of missingness matters. Block missingness (whole issuers disappearing for weeks) is informative and dangerous: it correlates with liquidity events, which correlate with returns. Random missingness is benign. The visual should make block patterns jump out immediately.Best implementation: order the y-axis (bonds) by hierarchical clustering on the missingness pattern, not alphabetically. Bonds with similar missingness profiles cluster together, and you'll see issuer/sector/rating structure emerge without ever looking at returns.C. Signal persistence heatmap.A lag × signal heatmap showing the autocorrelation of each signal cross-sectionally at lags 1d, 5d, 21d, 63d. This is the single most important diagnostic for signal construction: a signal with near-zero 1d autocorrelation is noisy and needs smoothing; a signal with autocorrelation still at 0.95 at 21d is so persistent that the 5d and 21d horizons are essentially the same bet.The visual should be a grid: rows are signals, columns are lags, color is rank autocorrelation. This immediately reveals which signals are redundant (similar persistence profiles → likely correlated → inflated effective multiplicity) and which horizons are actually distinct.D. The dependence structure diagnostic — this is the most underrated one.A signal correlation matrix visualized as a clustermap with dendrogram. But not the Pearson correlation of raw signals — the Spearman correlation of cross-sectional signal ranks, averaged over time. This tells you the effective dimensionality of your search space. If your 27-element search space (3 spreads × 3 horizons × 3 transforms) has only 4–5 eigenvalues above noise, your effective multiplicity is 4–5, not 27. The clustermap makes this visually obvious: tight clusters of near-identical signals that should be treated as one test.
